I'm not being hypocritical when I see death as caused by hijacked planes being smashed into buildings full of innocents as being different from a just war in retaliation.  Perhaps I'm a bit stilted on this point, but at least the folks that may, if we get into a bombing campaign or a ground war, that get killed will have been by accident (i.e. we won't be aiming for them) and because they couldn't clear out from a stated war zone.<br>
<br>
I'm intrigued by your assertion that the wars I mentioned included an entire country.  During WWII, the vast majority of the Japanese people had no real idea how the war was going, what their leaders were allowing to be done regionally and how that was percieved on a global scale.  In short, we weren't at war with the entire country of Japan as many of the people there would likely have balked if they really knew what was up.  How was that a more just war than this would be, as you imply?  If the government of a nation acts, then the nation acts.  If the people are not behind the government, then THEY must act to counter it.  If they don't then they are behind it by default.  In this case, there's an extra layer in that the govnerment is harboring criminals that we are after, but still, the conclusion is the same.<br>
<br>
Read the papers, brother.  Hundreds have already been arrested, and hundreds more are on the lamb.  We ARE clearing out or at least trying to find terrorist cells in America.  Don't suggest that we need to complete that job before we start looking elsewhere. . . <br>
