-Ram <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bdruzzilro86846.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=zolariarrowheart>Zolari Arrowheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(9/28/01 6:51:00 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Just my 2cp</span><hr size=1> I was 13 in the summer of 1990 when my family and I packed up and moved to Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. Two weeks after my 14th birthday we were evacuated as soon as we got the news that Kuwait had been invaded. My father, an Air Force Captain, had to stay in Riyadh. Less than three months later we were back in Riyadh. A month after we had gotten back my mother returned to the US to take of my sick Grandmother. My father showed my brother, who was 12 at the time and I how to wear gas masks and chemical suits.<br>
We still attended school and one day my friend brought some pictures her father had taken of the aftermath of the Invasion. They are still in my head, I will never forget them. Families in their cars burned to death just because they were on the road that day. Infants were in those burned cars, kids my age burned to death.  <br>
In January of 1991 the scuds were launched. My brother and I hid in my parents bedroom that my dad had sealed up with torn up trash bags and masking tape. My father told us to put on our masks and not to open the bedroom door for anyone not even him no matter how he yelled until the bombing stopped and even then we had to be absolutely sure it was safe. The house shook with every loud bang overhead and my brother and I were crying.  After everything calmed down hours later we were allowed to go back to our rooms to go to bed, needless to say I could not sleep. My mother called a few days later and told my dad that her mom had died.<br>
A couple of weeks later,we were evacuated. My brother and I sat in the barracks, near the airfield with other dependent families, waiting for the plane to get a flat tire fixed and heard the military radio scream yellow alert. It was another scud attack. One of the men went outside with his gun. One stayed inside with his in front of the door. We were told to huddle on the ground in the barracks, and not to get up. We were told that anyone that tried to get in would be shot no questions asked. The same went for anyone trying to get out. My brother and I sat on the floor with my friend, her little brother and mother. I began to realize that if the plane wouldn't have had a flat tire we would have been flying when the scuds and patriots were in the air overhead. <br>
My mother picked us up at the airport the next evening and cried. Every day my mother watched the news, waited and cried. My brother and I knew that we might not see our dad again. <br>
After the fighting had ended and some of the troops went home, we went back to Saudi. Cars were checked for bombs before entering the walled-in compounds where people of many nationalities lived. My father checked the car for bombs when we went outside the compound to go shopping before we were allowed to leave the stores. A couple years later, A small compound called OPM-SANG was bombed. Some of my parents friends worked there. Then, Khobar Towers in Dharhan was bombed. I returned to the US in 1995 for college while my parents remained until 2000.<br>
10 years later, I feel like I am in my parents bedroom again, crying and shaking in fear. But this time, I have nowhere to run to.<br>
<br>
Zolari Arrowheart<br>
39 Paladin<br>
Rutabaga Paradox<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/uladisarinja.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ladi Sarinja</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Druzzil Ro Member</span><br>  Posts: 147<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(9/28/01 9:07:26 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Just my 2cp</span><hr size=1> For those that knew what I was describing and understand the point of my post.... I wish you more hugs than you can handle. More love from friends and family that ya can ever expect. Noone should ever have to see or hear such things.<br>
<br>
Nods, I agree with kill the person behind NYC-WTC. Wholeheartedly. But the point of my post was just a reminder of sorts... what it is that will start up.. if we do go in with our guns blazin.<br>
<br>
Most of us that play EQ are actually people.. sittin at a computer in a dark room with ashtray full and o'erflowin with cigarette butts, 50+ soda cans on the floor next to an o'erfull trash can, 5 or 6 plates stacked haphazardly next to the computer case, and about 100 lil tiny pieces of paper with notes, locations, passwords, and a thousand tiny scribbles of things we don't wanna forget. Most of us are real live human beings.. full of pride, prejudice, love, and sense of self worth.<br>
<br>
Finally... many of us... I'd wager about half.. have been in the military.. have seen what happens when people fight. Not just on the news. All of it.<br>
<br>
It's those people I speak of when I beg caution from our leaders before they decide to start up a war, scuffle, or even tumble in the hay, with another land or country.<br>
<br>
Am I this freaky word ya try to call me? Pacifist? I don't think so. I'm all for bombin the remains of some asshole off the face of the planet for DARING to shake up my sense of security in the United States of America. I just beg caution.<br>
<br>
Lil story, if I may? Not that ya have a choice. I am human and I am in the above described room, typin.. and you can't stop me.<br>
<br>
Anyway.. I was in that foreign country that I wrote about in my first post. The only part of that post that did NOT apply to me was the fact that I have never seen a weapon used on another person. I thank God for that, every day.<br>
<br>
When I came back to America and I touched that lovely soil that we so proudly hold as ours, I thanked God for allowin me to come home to a land where I did NOT have to worry so much about what the plane o'erhead was gonna do. I was SAFE. I was on AMERICAN SOIL. I WAS IN THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA. I WAS SAFE. I've always firmly believed that nothin can TOUCH ME as long as I was in MY UNITED STATES of AMERICA. I... WAS... SAFE, damn it.<br>
<br>
(Laugh at that, if ya want.. but I am only human. I have my own fears and scary monsters in my closet... and I'm quite sure y'all got yours, too)<br>
<br>
Then.. Torf comes home from work early, wakes me up and pulls me to the living room to watch the television. Tis about 11am... Sept 11th. I will ne'er forget it.<br>
<br>
Why? Because MY UNITED STATES of AMERICA was no longer safe from the plane flyin o'erhead. MY HOME was threatened. The soil that I knew as my haven from the evils of the world was no longer safe. The ground shook, buildings fell, and many died. MANY.<br>
<br>
Now... am I ready and willing to head back o'erseas to kill some asshole who DARES to take that away from me? Most assuredly.<br>
<br>
Do I want someone in another country to feel as I did on Sept 11th? HELL NO. Why? Because it hurts. It brings tears to the surface of a face that does NOT like to show weakness by allowin them to flow.<br>
<br>
So, when ya sit there, in ya own dark lil room... remember.. yea, we owe someone a lot of pain.. but we need to try to contain the amount of pain we bestow.. for someone else may have the same feelings that I do.<br>
<br>
'Nuff said... I've typed way too much, already. <p>Ladi Sarinja<br>
57th Templar<br>
Leader, Clan Brigatta<br>
