<br>
Right now we are conducting an operation to get Osama Bin Laden and to exterminate his terrorist camps. This is being done by our special operations personnel (both people on the ground and air support). Both U.S. and British special operations units are on site now and have been for some time. This will last until we capture him, kill him, and determine that we have dealt his terrorist operations in Afghanistan a mortal blow. We are going after the ferret and his nest at the moment. For the first time in quite a very long time our special operations community has been un-muzzled. You may be surprised at what these people are capable of doing now that they have been allowed to do what they have always trained so hard for.<br>
<br>
As for what happens next I do not know? My guess is that the war will then be directed at nations which are known to sponsor terrorisim. These nations are Iraq, Sudan, Syria, Iran, Algeria, etc. How this will be done I dont know? Also it becomes tricky at this point. I'm not sure to what level this war will be waged? I do think that President Bush and his people are building up a coalition that will last the duration and be able to support and stomach a conventional war against the above mentioned countries. What do you say to a nation like Iran that has in the past solidly sponsored terrorists but now wants to try and get away from that past? Or do they? I fully believe and feel a conventional war against any nation which sponsors terrorism is just and right. You wage it as you would any other war, you go in and seek to destroy their military, government, and industrial sectors. You reduce their ability to wage war, or in this case their will or capability to sponsor terrorism. Thats what it takes to secure your safety, freedom, future of your nation and civilization. Its been done in the past when nations were threatened, its time to do it again.<br>
<br>
Many people here like to view these Islamic radicals as some sort of holy supermen. I think thats BS. They die like anyone else. Momar Qhadiffi was a very resolute anti-western radical. His main occupation was running Libya and supporting/waging terrorism. This was back when all the dance clubs in Europe were getting bombed and the Pan Am flight went down at Lockerbie. When Reagan bombed him he stopped. Wheres Momar now? Olive vendor? Camel jockeying across the Sahara? Sure it took a near direct hit to his house and the death of his daughter, but nontheless he shut the fuck up and promptly made a career change. Thats what it takes folks. A very mean and resolute retaliation. <br>
<br>
What the terrorists did was a clear and unquestionable act of war. With 5,000+ dead theres no question of that. You can bet your bottom dollar that there will be more attacks of this magnitude. It may be attacks at infrastructure next time, but regardless it will be of great magnitude. So you have a choice. Do you cower down, hope the next attack doesnt get you, and maybe our politicans can parlay with these devils? AKA the the Neville Chamberlin method.  Or do you engage in a military campaign to exterminate your enemies, enemies which have clearly demonstrated they will give their lives to take yours, your family, and your way of life.. I dont know about you all, but if someone on my block murdered my family I'd kill the one responsible without a second thought.<br>
<br>
I also think this has the potential to get extremely ugly. /predictions on .. I predict that after some time is put in to the Intelligence gathering effort we will see that support for Osama Bin Laden and anti-western terrorist organizations ran MUCH deeper in the islamic world than we had originally thought..../predictions off ... And we may even be suprised to find out that some of our &quot;friends&quot; actually were quite friendly with Bin Laden as well. This has the potential to become very nasty, especially if such support turns out to be widespread and deep it could be likened to a conflict between culture and civilization in a sense. The war on terrorism could easily turn in to a war against the middle east, or the arabic nations in general? It could be done, but it would definitely be a step up from what they are envisioning now. Who knows whats at the bottom of this pandoras box? Time will tell.<br>
<br>
